    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's pretty scary. It sounds like they're basically trying to find any tiny way to blame me for stuff that might not even be my fault. Are there specific words in a clause like that that usually signal they're trying to be \"sneaky\" or hide things that could come back to bite me later? Like, what should I be looking for to see if they're being predatory?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, that is a very common tactic, and you should definitely look for specific \"red flag\" phrases that indicate the other party is trying to be overly broad or hide their own risks. You should specifically watch out for words like \"any and all,\" \"whatever kind,\" or \"arising out of or occurring in connection with,\" as these are legal jargon designed to cast a wide net over any possible scenario, including things completely unrelated to your work.\n\nAnother sneaky term to spot is \"gross negligence\" or \"willful misconduct\" missing from the definition of when you have to pay, because without those qualifiers, you could be liable for simple mistakes or even errors made by their own team. Additionally, check if they are demanding you cover \"attorneys' fees\" or \"costs\" without a clear limit, as this can drain your savings even if the lawsuit is dropped.\n\nIf you see a clause that tries to shift liability for things like \"deficiencies\" or \"penalties\" that are clearly the other party's fault, that is a sign they are being predatory. You should definitely negotiate to cap your liability at a specific dollar amount or ensure you only cover your own direct negligence, rather than their entire legal exposure",
      "source": "target",
